@node OIA "Operator Information Area"

OIA (Operator Information Area)

The OIA gives information regarding the status of the session,
including information on keyboard states, and connection status.
The OIA is the boxed area at the bottom of the tn3270 window.
The indicators, from left to right are:

  Connect status
  Keyboard Lock
  Current Host
  Insert Mode Indicator
  Numlock Mode Indicator

@endnode

@node PREFS "Preferences Overview"

Preferences

TN3270 preferences are kept in plain (editable) ASCII text
files. TN3270 will alway attempt to load the 'defaults.prefs'
file from the program directory. In addition, it may set or
reset additional items based on a project (saved prefs icon)
file and Icon Tooltypes, if defined. Keymaps are kept in
separate files, and are referenced by name in prefs files.
This modular approach, which may seem awkward at first,
allows preferences to be cascaded with little effort. This
will allow, for example, one change to your keymap to be
effective across all of your custom configurations, instead
of having to change each one. A little forethought should
go a long way.

Each line of a preference file may contain one preference
item, consisting of a keyword, and equal sign, and the
desired value. Keywords must start in the first column.
There should be no space beside the equal sign on either
side. Invalid line are quietly ignored. Lines starting with
a semicolon are considered comments.

These are the current preference keywords:

CODEPAGE
Specifies an alternate @{"codepage map" link CODEPAGE} to use
Example: CODEPAGE=PROGDIR:codepages/037

KEYMAP
Specifes a @{"keymapping file" link KEYMAP} to use.
Example: KEYMAP=PROGDIR:default.keys

FONT
Specifies the primary font to use for the tn3270 screen.
This should be a MONOSPACED font. Keep in mind that your
screen resolution must be sufficently large to accomidate
a full 80 columns of text plus a few extra pixels for a
window border, or operation will be impared.
Example: FONT=topaz.font

FONTSIZE
The Y size, or height of the primary font.
Example: FONTSIZE=8

ALTFONT
Specifies the secondary font that may be toggled with the
item on the PREFS menu. It has the same condsiderations
as FONT above.

ALTFONTSIZE
FONTSIZE for the ALTFONT.

FONTBOLD
Specifies the default BOLD state for the font. Use YES and
NO as vaules.
Example: FONTBOLD=NO

OIAFONT
Specifies an alternate font for the @{"Operator Information Area" link OIA}.
This may be proportional. The default 3270dodads.font has
special characters for graphic display. When replacing this
font, you may need to define the OIA_#? strings, see below.

OIAFONTSIZE
The Y size, or height of the OIA font. The default size is 13
points, and a defined alternate size of the default font is 7.
If you are using a custom OIAFONT, indicate the appropriate
size.

OIA_OFFLINE
OIA_NVT
OIA_ONLINE
Substitutions for the default OIA connection indicators.

OIA_CLOCK
OIA_SYSTEM
OIA_LOCKED
Substitutions for the default OIA keyboard lock indicators.

OIA_INS
Substitution for the default OIA Inser Mode indicator.

OIA_NUMLK
Substitution for the default OIA Numlock indicator.

SCREEN
A public screen name on which to open. If omitted, the default
public screen is used.
Example: SCREEN=Workbench

The following keywords are recognized, but not yet supported.
TERMTYPE
HOST
PORT
WINDOW_TOP
WINDOW_LEFT
APPICON
PROJECTICON
STARTUP
MACRO

@endnode

@node KEYMAP "Key Mapping Overview"

The total keyboard layout is a combination of two independent
configuration files. The first is the @{"codepage" link CODEPAGE} or mapping
of Amiga characters to EBCDIC. The second is an assignment of
the various 3270 functions to the Amiga keyboard.

All keymap assignments use single key presses on the Amiga
keyboard. A single key press can be modified by the shift,
alt and ctrl keys. The numeric keypad and the Del key are
given special exceptions.

If no keymap file is specified, a @{"default keymap" link DEFAULTKEY} is used.

The keymap definition are stored in a standard ASCII file, and
may be edited directly if desired. The keyboard section of the
prefs editor shields you from many of the details of this, but
for the adventurous, here is a description of a keymap file.

One keymap entry per line, lines begining with a semicolon are
considered comments. Any line which does not make sense to the
keymap reader is ignored. Lines have the following format:

table key function data

'table' represents the internal key table for this entry
   Vanilla   - includes printable characters and ASCII controls
   Raw       - keys with no printable representation (like F? keys)
   ShiftRaw  - Raw keys with a shift key held down
   AltRaw    - Raw keys with an alt key held down
   CtrlRaw   - Raw key with the Ctrl key held down
   Numpad    - key on the numeric keypad
   AltNumpad - numeric kepad key with an alt key held down

Note that tn3270 does not use multiple qualifiers (such as
Ctrl+Alt.)

'key' represents either the character value for Vanilla keys,
or the scan code for raw keys. This value can be expressed in
a keymap file as a single printable character or as a pair of
hex digits representing the scancode or character.

'function' is the 3270 function assigned to this key. See the
complete @{"function list" link FUNCTIONS} for possible values.
Note that all codepage character are added to the keymap as 
'char' functions.

'data' is similar to the key parameter, and used for functions
which require additional data. Presently only the 'char'
function uses this. In that case it represents the EBCDIC
character to be generated.

@endnode

@node FUNCTIONS "3270 Functions"

The following 3270 functions are available.

   function	description
   ---------	-------------------------------------------
   backtab	move to previous start of field
   char		insert data character in buffer
   clear        clear (AID)
   cursel	cursor select (AID)
   delete	delete character under cursor
   down		cursor down one line
   dup		duplicate (application dependent)
   enter	enter (AID)
   erase	delete character to left
   eraseeof	erase to end of current field
   eraseinput	erase all unprotected fields
   fieldend	move cursor to end of field
   fielderase	erase current field
   fieldmark	field mark (application dependent)
   home		move cursor to top left field
   insert	toggle insert/overstrike modes
   left		move cursor left one position
   left2	move cursor left two positions
   monocase	supress lower case
   newline	move cursor to next leftmost field
   null		does nothing
   numlock	toggle numbers/functions on keypad
   pa1		program attention 1 (AID)
   pa2		program attention 2 (AID)
   pa3		program attention 3 (AID)
   pf1		program function 1 (AID)
    -		...
   pf24		program function 24 (AID)
   print	dump screen image to printer
   reset	clear keyboard lock
   reshow	redisplay screen
   right	move cursor right one position
   right2	move cursor right two positions
   selectpen	simulate selector pen
   tab		move cursor to start of next field
   testreq	test request (AID)
   up		move cursor up one line
   wordback	move cursor back one work
   wordend	move cursor to end of word
   worderase	erase the current word
   wordtab	move cursor to next word

The following functions provide setting and moving by alternate
tab stops. They were part of the original code, and have not been
removed. They also have not been extensively tested. They do not
represent 'standard' 3270 functions.
   cleartab
   colbak
   coltab
   deltab
   indent	
   sethome
   setmargin
   settab
   undent

@endnode

