@node CODEPAGE "Codepages and EBCDIC Variations"
A codepage file consists of a 256 byte table containing native
Amiga characters presented in EBCDIC order. This would be much
simpler if EBCDIC was a single code, like ECMA Latin 1, but is
is not. From a purely historical perspective, EBCDIC matches
the old hollerith punched card code more closely than anything
else. Its early incarnations had little if any provision for
anything other than the basic set of alpha-numerics used in
USA english. As the scope extended, a few select spots in the
EBCDIC space were assigned to 'national use' characters. These
gave a quick way to use EBCDIC in non-USA english environments.
Over the years, these EBCDIC variations were flushed out with
a large complement of characters, but the spaces reserved for
the old national use chracters, for the most part, retained the
differing values, resulting in a whole range of mappings refered
to as codepges. tn3270 comes with mappings for all of the
common codepages which can be directly mapped to the Amiga's
native ECMA Latin-1 chracter set. These are:

  037  (default) USA, Belgium, Brazil, Canada bilingual,
       Netherlands, Portugal
  273  Austria, Germany
  277  Denmark, Norway
  278  Finland, Sweden
  280  Italy
  284  Latin America, Spain
  285  UK
  297  France
  500  Multinational
  871  Iceland

With the supplied codepage sets, all Amiga keys which generate
Latin 1 display characters translate to their EBCDIC CECP 697/1
equivalents.

Other codepages require additional Amiga keymaps and fonts,
but could be added, if desired. The gen_cp.c source is
included in the distribution as an aid to adapting tn3270
to non-latin 1 codepages.
@endnode

@node CHANGES "Recent Change History"

Alpha 3b - inital public release

Alpha 3d
- hopefully fixed the occasional and mysterious keyboard lag.
- should see some speed-up in output, especially on slower machines.
- requester instead of stdio output on exception exit.
- no longer complains about usergroup.library or asks for 'AMITCP:'
  when TCP/IP is not up.
- fixed serious error in the exit logic which could cause a guru.

Alpha 4.0
- A whole new world, menus, oia, connect window.

- Although a bit awkward now, the FONT can now be changed!

- Numerous internal 3270 handling tweaks

- Changes to EBCDIC to ECMA Latin 1 mapping, now uses loadable
  code page sets.

- Custom key maps are possible.

@endnode

@node FUTURE "The future of tn3270"

Future

The Alpha 4 series will be concentrating on the user interface.
The near term releases will be enabling all those disabled
menu option, adding thing like rexx support, and other neat
goodies.

Although any bugs brought to my attention will be addressed, the
current plan is to postpone adding some much needed features to
the underlying 3270 emulation, until the interface is to a
fairly complete and stable point. (Color and attribute support
are examples of the 'much needed features'.)

This package will be developed to a point just because I need it
for remote suport of some IBM systems. After that point, any
additional develompent will depend on the encouragement of the
program's user base. Alpha 4 is being publicly released in the
hopes of obtaining feedback from anyone in the Amiga community
which might benefit from a tn3270 client. Please send comments,
suggestions, bug reports, and any other communications to:

	ragriffi@sprynet.com  (Richard Griffith)

I would like to thank all of those who have written to me about
tn3270, as it is very helpful to know that someone else cares
about this effort. Thanks again.

@endnode

